The [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) is a British daily [middle-market](/Middle-market_newspaper) [tabloid](/Tabloid_journalism) conservative newspaper, first making its appearance on the newsstands of London in 1896. This publication, a stalwart of the British press, has expanded its reach considerably over the decades, establishing a [Scottish](/Scotland) edition in 1947 and an [Irish](/Ireland) edition in 2006. Its digital counterpart, [MailOnline](/MailOnline), operates as a distinct entity with its own editorial team, though much of its content originates from the printed paper, a testament to the symbiotic, if sometimes strained, relationship between print and digital journalism [5] [6] [7].

The paper's ownership rests with the [Daily Mail and General Trust](/Daily_Mail_and_General_Trust), a corporate entity overseen by [Jonathan Harmsworth, 4th Viscount Rothermere](/Jonathan_Harmsworth,_4th_Viscount_Rothermere). As a direct great-grandson of one of the original co-founders, his influence is considerable, serving as both chairman and controlling shareholder. Despite this familial legacy, the daily editorial decisions are typically delegated to a dedicated team under the leadership of the appointed editor. Since 17 November 2021, [Ted Verity](/Ted_Verity) has held this pivotal role, succeeding [Geordie Greig](/Geordie_Greig).

In 2014, a demographic survey revealed that the average age of a [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) reader hovered around 58, marking it as the British major daily with the lowest proportion of readers between 15 and 44 years old [9]. Intriguingly, and somewhat uniquely within the landscape of British daily newspapers, women constitute a slight majority of its readership, typically ranging from 52–55% [10]. As of February 2020, the paper maintained an average daily circulation of approximately 1.13 million copies [11]. The period between April 2019 and March 2020 saw its average daily readership reach around 2.18 million individuals, with roughly 1.41 million falling into the [ABC1](/NRS_social_grade) demographic (middle and upper-middle class) and 0.77 million in the [C2DE](/NRS_social_grade) demographic (working class and non-working population) [12]. Its online platform, [MailOnline](/MailOnline), boasted an impressive reach, attracting over 218 million unique visitors each month in 2020, underscoring its significant digital footprint [13].

Despite consistent criticism regarding its journalistic integrity, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) has accumulated a notable collection of accolades. It has been honored with [The Press Awards](/The_Press_Awards)' National Newspaper of the Year title nine times since 1994, with the most recent win recorded in 2019 [14]. The [Society of Editors](/Society_of_Editors) also recognized it as the 'Daily Newspaper of the Year' for 2020 [15]. However, these commendations exist in stark contrast to persistent criticisms. The paper has faced scrutiny for its perceived unreliability, a propensity for [sensationalist](/Sensationalism) reporting, and a track record of publishing what many consider inaccurate scare stories, particularly concerning scientific and medical research [16] [17] [18] [19]. Allegations of [plagiarism](/Plagiarism) and [copyright infringement](/Copyright_infringement) have also plagued its reputation [20] [21] [22] [23]. This contentious history culminated in a significant decision in February 2017 when the [English Wikipedia](/English_Wikipedia) community formally banned the use of the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) as a reliable source for factual claims, a move that highlighted serious concerns about its editorial practices [24] [25] [26].

## Overview

Initially, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) presented itself in the more traditional [broadsheet](/Broadsheet) format, a common sight for serious newspapers of its era. However, in a strategic shift coinciding with its 75th anniversary on 3 May 1971, the paper transitioned to a more manageable compact format [27]. This move wasn't just a physical change; it also marked the absorption of its sister publication, the [Daily Sketch](/Daily_Sketch), which had previously operated as a [tabloid](/Tabloid_journalism) under the same corporate umbrella. This consolidation allowed the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) to streamline operations and potentially capture a broader readership. The publishing entity behind the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)), the [Daily Mail and General Trust](/Daily_Mail_and_General_Trust) (DMGT), maintains a public presence on the [London Stock Exchange](/London_Stock_Exchange), reflecting its status as a significant media conglomerate.

According to the meticulous records of the [Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)](/Audit_Bureau_of_Circulations_(UK)), the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) registered gross daily sales of 1,134,184 copies in February 2020 [11]. The paper's political leanings are clearly reflected in its readership; a December 2004 survey indicated that a substantial 53% of [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) readers cast their votes for the [Conservative Party (UK)](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), a stark contrast to the 21% who supported [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and 17% for the [Liberal Democrats (UK)](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)) [28]. This demographic insight underscores its entrenched position within the British political landscape. [Viscount Rothermere](/Jonathan_Harmsworth,_4th_Viscount_Rothermere), the current chairman and principal shareholder, maintains that the paramount concern is sustaining the paper's circulation. He famously articulated before a [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords) [select committee](/Select_committee_(United_Kingdom)) the principle that "we need to allow editors the freedom to edit," implying that the newspaper's editor possesses the autonomy to shape editorial policy, including its political allegiances [29]. This statement, of course, leaves room for interpretation regarding the *true* extent of that "freedom." On 17 November 2021, [Ted Verity](/Ted_Verity) assumed a newly expanded, seven-day editorial role, taking charge of all Mail newspapers, a portfolio that includes the flagship [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)), [The Mail on Sunday](/The_Mail_on_Sunday), and *You* magazine [30].

## History

### Early history

Advertisement by the Daily Mail for insurance against [Zeppelin](/Zeppelin) attacks during the [First World War](/First_World_War)

The [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) was conceived and brought to life by the visionary, if somewhat controversial, brothers [Alfred Harmsworth](/Alfred_Harmsworth,_1st_Viscount_Northcliffe) (who would later become Viscount Northcliffe) and [Harold Harmsworth](/Harold_Harmsworth,_1st_Viscount_Rothermere) (eventually Viscount Rothermere). Its inaugural issue hit the streets on 4 May 1896, and it was an immediate, undeniable sensation [31]:28. Priced at a mere halfpenny, it dramatically undercut its London daily competitors, which typically retailed for a full penny. This aggressive pricing strategy, coupled with a more populist tone and a refreshingly concise approach to news coverage, resonated deeply with the public. The initial circulation target was an ambitious 100,000 copies, yet the first day's print run soared to an astonishing 397,215, necessitating the rapid acquisition of additional printing facilities to keep pace with demand. By 1899, its circulation had climbed to 500,000, and by 1902, in the wake of the [Boer Wars](/Boer_War), it surpassed a million, solidifying its status as the largest newspaper in the world [33] [34]. This meteoric rise prompted [Lord Salisbury](/Robert_Gascoyne-Cecil,_3rd_Marquess_of_Salisbury), the 19th-century [Prime Minister of the United Kingdom](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom), to famously dismiss the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) as "a newspaper produced by office boys for office boys," a remark that, while intended as a slight, inadvertently captured its populist appeal [32]:590–591.

With Harold meticulously managing the intricate business operations and Alfred steering the editorial ship, the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) swiftly adopted an unyielding [imperialist](/Imperialism) political stance. This was particularly evident in its fervently patriotic coverage of the [Second Boer War](/Second_Boer_War), a period during which critics argued it sacrificed objective reporting for a jingoistic narrative [35]. Beyond its political posturing, the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) also ingeniously sought to captivate its readers through compelling human interest stories, engaging serials, diverse features, and enticing competitions [36]:5. It was a pioneering force in recognizing and actively cultivating the burgeoning market of female readers, dedicating an entire section to women's interests [37] [36]:16. Furthermore, it notably hired one of the earliest female war correspondents, [Sarah Wilson](/Sarah_Wilson_(war_correspondent)), who delivered dispatches from the front lines of the [Second Boer War](/Second_Boer_War) [38] [36]:27.

In a move that revolutionized newspaper distribution, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) began simultaneously printing in both Manchester and London in 1900, becoming the first national newspaper to achieve this feat. Prior to this, in 1899, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) had already established a system of special trains to transport London-printed papers northward, highlighting its early commitment to national reach. This innovative production method was subsequently adopted by the [Daily Sketch](/Daily_Sketch) in 1909, the [Daily Express](/Daily_Express) in 1927, and eventually became standard practice for virtually all other national newspapers. Production of the [Scottish Daily Mail](/Scottish_Daily_Mail) was later relocated from Edinburgh to the Deansgate plant in Manchester in 1968. For a period, [The People](/The_Sunday_People) also utilized the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) presses in Deansgate. However, in 1987, printing operations at Deansgate ceased, with northern editions thereafter being produced at other facilities owned by [Associated Newspapers](/Associated_Newspapers).

During the early 20th century, the paper vigorously championed against the perceived "[Yellow Peril](/Yellow_Peril)," a xenophobic narrative warning of alleged dangers posed by Chinese immigration to the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) [39]. This particular theme, however, eventually faded as the escalating Anglo-German naval race presented a more immediate and "plausible" threat to the [British Empire](/British_Empire) [39]. In alignment with other Conservative publications, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) skillfully leveraged the naval race to criticize the Liberal governments in power from 1906 onwards, accusing them of being overly cautious and indecisive in their response to the Tirpitz plan, Germany's ambitious naval expansion program.

The [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) was also known for its ambitious and often extravagant stunts. In 1906, it famously offered a substantial £10,000 prize for the first successful flight from London to [Manchester](/Manchester), a challenge that captured the public's imagination. This was followed by a £1,000 prize for the first aerial crossing of the [English Channel](/English_Channel) [31]:29. *[Punch](/Punch_(magazine))* magazine, ever the satirist, found the idea so ludicrous that it mockingly offered £10,000 for the first flight to [Mars](/Mars). Yet, by 1910, both of the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(newspaper))'s challenging aviation prizes had been claimed. The paper continued to sponsor [aviation prizes](/Daily_Mail_aviation_prizes) intermittently until 1930 [40]. Not all its journalistic endeavors were met with praise, however. Virginia Woolf, a keen observer of media, criticized the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) as an unreliable newspaper. She specifically cited a July 1900 report during the [Boxer Rebellion](/Boxer_Rebellion) that falsely claimed "every one of the Europeans was put to the sword in a most atrocious manner," asserting that the entire European community in Beijing had been massacred [41]. A month later, in August 1900, the [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) published an account of the relief of the Western Legations in Beijing, where Westerners and thousands of Chinese Christians had indeed been under siege by the Boxers [41].

Leading up to the [First World War](/First_World_War), the paper faced accusations of warmongering, primarily for its alarmist reports suggesting that Germany harbored intentions to dismantle the [British Empire](/British_Empire) [31]:29. When war inevitably broke out, Northcliffe's vocal advocacy for [conscription](/Conscription) was initially met with considerable controversy. However, his stance was ultimately vindicated when conscription was formally introduced in 1916 [42]. A particularly contentious moment occurred on 21 May 1915, when Northcliffe publicly criticized [Lord Kitchener](/Horatio_Kitchener), the revered [Secretary of State for War](/Secretary_of_State_for_War), over issues concerning weapons and munitions. Kitchener, a national hero in the eyes of many, saw the paper's circulation plummet from 1,386,000 to a mere 238,000. This public outcry was so severe that fifteen hundred members of the [London Stock Exchange](/London_Stock_Exchange) demonstratively burned unsold copies of the paper and called for a widespread boycott of the Harmsworth Press. Prime Minister [H. H. Asquith](/H._H._Asquith) went so far as to accuse the paper of disloyalty to the nation.

When Kitchener tragically died, the [Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation)) controversially framed it as a "great stroke of luck" for the [British Empire](/British_Empire) [31]:32. The paper maintained its critical stance on Asquith's prosecution of the war, a consistent pressure that some argue contributed to his resignation on 5 December 1916 [43]. His successor, [David Lloyd George](/David_Lloyd_George), extended an invitation for Northcliffe to join his cabinet, presumably hoping to neutralize his potent criticism of the government. Northcliffe, however, declined the offer [44]. Reflecting on Northcliffe's profound impact, [Piers Brendon](/Piers_Brendon) offered a scathing assessment: "Northcliffe's methods made the Mail the most successful newspaper hitherto seen in the history of journalism. But by confusing gewgaws with pearls, by selecting the paltry at the expense of the significant, by confirming atavistic prejudices, by oversimplifying the complex, by dramatising the humdrum, by presenting stories as entertainment and by blurring the difference between news and views, Northcliffe titillated, if he did not debauch, the public mind; he polluted, if he did not poison, the wells of knowledge." [45] A stark, yet perhaps accurate, summary of the early [Daily Mail](/Daily_Mail_(disambiguation))'s legacy.

### Inter-war period

